text:
#usat2018inphotos 
follow along as we highlight some of the best photos from usa today network photographers.

we're highlighting one photo from every day this year. to see all the memorable moments from 2018, click the link in our bio. 
from the photographer, dan macmeden: this began as a portrait of a few women that wanted to come forward to tell their #metoo stories, which grew to 15, then 18, then 20 and finally 26. when this assignment came in, the #metoo was gaining traction at an incredible pace, but all the stories usually involved well known celebrities and people in power that we consider public figures and in our minds have a much more arm‚Äôs length view of.  all of these women are working in the entertainment industry, but in the real-world workday jobs that, like myself, are all behind the camera and not household names, yet strive every day to make everything else look good for all those celebrities and ‚Äúabove the line‚Äù people. my memory of this shoot was how appreciative they were to have us tell their story in a dignified and respectful manner and i was honored to help do that.

text:
as i‚Äôm sitting here fine-tuning diversity statements and my personal essays for grad school applications, i‚Äôve been doing a lot of reflecting. part of me is scared to include my story of sexual harassment in industry and academia, for fear of seeming ‚Äúdifficult‚Äù. and here we are again, the constant battle women go through when just trying to decide on whether to report an incident. but it‚Äôs important for my story to be told, because we need to be talking about it. i cannot wait to further my education and dive back into research for a phd in geology, but i‚Äôm passionate about gender equality, diversity and inclusion in the workplace. this is a big piece of who i am now, and i don‚Äôt want any other young women or minorities to have to experience the hurdles i went through to get help.
.
.
.
.

text:
men‚Äôs behavior change experts have shown that education about women‚Äôs rights and male privilege does not end abuse. accountability and monitoring are the only deterrents. typically men who abuse their partners - if they are caught - are assigned to anger management classes or batterer intervention programs and sent back to their vulnerable targets. the legal system fails women because it fails to identify the problem: misogyny. we fail victims when abuse is explained as mental illness, attachment style, substance use or any other substitute for men‚Äôs historic ‚Äúright to own their woman.‚Äù ¬∂

typically churches fail too. that‚Äôs because sin has not traditionally been defined as systemic ‚Äúisms‚Äù such white dominance, male dominance etc. why not? because of who has been in a position to formulate ethics and theology: those with privilege. while christ came into the margins with a fearsome and decisive stance of submission to those without power, the church is in constant need of reform to return to that value. ¬∂

with that context in mind, checking an abuser - challenging his beliefs - will naturally fly in the face of our upbringing in christian quietude. the church has enshrined avoiding decisive action towards abusers, maintaining social structures, and the inequality of women. additionally, our human leaning is towards the tribe: a victim is wired for belonging and so she stays. the perpetrator is wired for belonging and so he does not exercise these entitlements outside the relationship. the bystander is wired for belonging and so will seek to eliminate the victim‚Äôs testimony to remain with the group.¬∂ knowing this, when the victim gives you permission to check the abuser, use your tribe. go with someone else. call an advocate hotline before and after if you are struggling with a church that doesn‚Äôt get it. use consequences. costs are more persuasive than words. if you have spoken to the victim, follow through for her. if you have told her what he‚Äôs doing is wrong, be willing to say the same to him. otherwise, the victim shoulders the burden of moral conscience. she needs clarity and inclusion from her tribe (you) which should be displayed in word and deed.

text:
hi there,

it‚Äôs been awhile since i‚Äôve introduced myself. i am a yoga teacher and student, nature lover, aztec pattern enthusiast, dog mom, animal foster, interpretive car dancer, and a sexual assault survivor. all of those are parts of me, but none of them define me. i‚Äôve recently found that my dharma in life is to turn my own pain into power and help women who experience sexual trauma find vulnerability and fulfillment in their lives once again. stay tuned for more information about my online mentorship program and expect lots of trauma-informed tid bits on here moving forward. in the meantime, please introduce yourself in the comments below or dm me and let me know how i can help you.

ps: i created a free monthly intentions template just for you! find it at alisaandrea.com

text:
#barbietoo  before i left the house i made sure to dress in something loose that would not be too distracting. as i walk the streets of new york at night,one hand holds my groceries tightly, the other holds my pocket knife. i walk with urgency, my hoodie is up and my headphones in and,which are not playing music, act like a barrier between the men who catcalls and whistles at me. i see a masculine shadow at the end of the street, but i cannot see its owner. i fear it‚Äôs a man awaiting my passing. i make a detour and walk across the street. 
as i usually do on a weekend night, i was clubbing and hanging out with my girls. i normally go to gay clubs, but this weekend i went to a straight club.  once i felt a strong grip on my ass, i turned around to say what the hell, but this 6 foot tall frat guy in a polo would not look at me. this is the first time i  had my ass grabbed unsolicitedly. they have the balls to grab me, but they don‚Äôt own up to their actions. every 5 minutes i would take a headcount of my girls because the cocky boys would not listen to us when we said we did not want to grind with them. this was the first night where i saw that the boys were not listening to no. it made me wonder why they felt because it was dark and the music was loud that they could do what they want. i was not being listened to. ‚Äúthere is no greater threat to women than men? we‚Äôre the number one threat!‚Äù said louis c.k. in his hbo special. when are men taught to acknowledge boundaries? i should be able to leave and feel safe wherever i go without having to worry. i am tired with the way that men are treating me and other women. every women has there own story with harassment, but to tell mine i am using barbie as my proxy. when i was younger i looked up to her and she was a beacon of indepence and i vividly remember watching rapunzel barbie in my bubblegum pink room thinking ‚Äúlook at all that she can do for herself‚Äù. #photo #photography #art #camera #canon #fujifilm #fujitx1 #digital #digitalphoto #digitalphotography #digitalphotos #mirrorless #metoo #barbie #pink #hair #violent #ken #sexualassult

text:
what a world we could have if we came into each relationship- whether that be friends or beloved already full?
what if we came into our relationships not with the score card of everything the other hadn‚Äôt done for us, or upset about expectations never said but our needs met.  our hearts full?
women tend to bond over stories- and if we haven‚Äôt taken the time to fill our own cup those stories are complaints- usually about men, sometimes other women. 
i definitely have fallen into that trap- thinking that by complaining we were bonding. 
instead, we meet our beloved with emotional needs already met...how awesome is that?

here‚Äôs why- i look forward to a world where we support each other, we push each other and we are better women, mothers, wives, business owners and better people in line for coffee or the freeway.  we sleep better, eat better and teach the younger generation self care is not an optional luxury.  the world where women are turned on, lit up and know just what they want and need. 
the dali lama said that the western woman will save the world. let‚Äôs prove him right. 
fill your own cup before you turn to your beloved and expect something from him (or her) and if you were never shown how(no worries i wasn‚Äôt either) call me. üòâü§óüòäüòç

text: a man. a mess. an exit. big food world news of the day is that longtime four seasons restaurant managing partner julian niccolini was let go after a cloud of sexual misconduct followed him from the old restaurant to the new, casting its shadow across even its reviews in the age of #metoo. when pete wells of the new york times gave the new restaurant one star, attributing the low ranking solely to niccolini‚Äôs presence despite raving about the food, the writing was on the wall. an odd conclusion to many years of covering this restaurant‚Äôs characters and fate, but an appropriate one. some messes are too big to be swept under the rug. #food #restaurant #nyc

episode 38: consent is sexy.
@avitable and @simplysarahg_ welcome landon funk, founder of the @funky_feminist movement, blog, and podcast, for a revelatory episode about consent. is "no means no" an appropriate response to consent or should we focus on "yes means yes" instead? how do you work ongoing consent into a night of sex and fireworks? your hosts and landon talk about how easy consent really can be as a concept when you strip away your privilege, put on someone else's shoes, and have a little empathy. visit funkyfeminist.com for more information on landon's podcast and to listen to episode 3 where sarah is a featured guest.

text:
new piece in @kidsstoppress on the aftermath of the #metoo crisis and what it means for us as parents. there have been several reactions to the #metoo movement but what i keep thinking about is what we can do as parents to ensure that we don't raise another generation of entitled abusive men, or women who suffer in silence. i penned down my thoughts as a letter from concerned parents to their sons, with a promise that this generation of parents will do things differently, and hopefully break the vicious cycle of abuse and silence. this is part of a two-part series with another letter addressed to daughters coming up soon. link in bio. .
.

does your organization have an internal complaints committee that redresses cases of sexual harassment of women at workplace? do get in touch with us here if you want to set one up and also undertake capacity building training of your employees at workplace. centre for social research is part of several organizations' internal complaints committee that includes private and public sector. to generate awareness leading to resolution and mitigation of sexual harassment at workplace, we undertake training on the same. the training requires minimum 3 hours and maximum of 16 hours for it to be effectively administered. we strongly recommend every organisation that has more than 10 employees to sensitize their employees on the law and the implementation. contact us to book a training. send a dm!

win two books & a badge!
closing wednesday 19th dec 6pm.
-
in need of an xmas prezzie for a feminist pal? we‚Äôve got you!
-
@profile.books kindly sent us a copy of mary beard‚Äôs bestselling feminist manifesto ‚Äòwomen & power‚Äô which has recently been updated. a year on since #metoo, beard looks at how the discussions have moved on during this time, and how that intersects with issues of rape and consent, and the stories men tell themselves to support their actions. in trademark beardian style, using examples ancient and modern, beard argues, 'it's time for change - and now!'
-
we‚Äôre also giving away a copy of our book ‚Äò100 women i know‚Äô a collection of accounts of rape and sexual assault. the stories in this book are from women that the editor phoebe knows personally, but aims to bring together and foster solidarity between everyone who has been a victim of sexual violence. by exposing the common threads in each story, 100 women i know demonstrates the need to redefine rape within society and to further the understanding of consent to help prevent young men and women from becoming perpetrators or survivors of sexual violence. the book gives a voice to all of the brave women who shared their stories and continues the much needed conversation on sexual violence. published by @brkthehbt
-

via world - imelda cortez, a 20-year-old woman in el salvador, who was jailed with attempted murder after she gave birth to her rapist‚Äôs baby in a toilet has been freed. cortez was rushed to the hospital in april 2017 after she gave birth to a baby girl fathered by her stepfather, who had raped and sexually abused her since she was 12, in the toilet. cortez said she did not know she was pregnant, but the doctor at the hospital suspected she had tried to abort the baby and called the authorities. cortez was then arrested and handed a 20 year jail sentence after prosecutors argued that failing to tell anyone about her pregnancy or seek medical attention for the baby amounted to attempted murder under the country‚Äôs laws, which completely bans abortions. however, on monday, a court ruled that cortez had not tried to kill her child and that she was free to go home. the judge concluded that the court could not have expected her to act differently given the emotional and psychological damage inflicted by the sexual violence she had suffered since childhood. cortez was greeted by family members and supporters outside the courtroom. (üì∑: getty, reuters)

text:
introducing the ‚Äúthe vagina monologues meets ted talks, meets the moth‚Äú.
i will be sharing my story "herstory" this thursday evening at the @feminine_harbor and the kw art gallery present the light stories. 
if you missed out or loved the woke women's night held at @juiciyoga , this is for you. 
i am deeply honoured to know @carolinapmiranda and to be in relationship with the vehicle of change she is bringing to this community and to this world. buy your ticket in the event page below & invite a friend! hope to see you there!  feminine harbor and the kitchener waterloo art gallery present: the l.i.g.h.t. stories.

4 women, of 4 different generations and 4 diverse cultural backgrounds, sharing real-life stories combined with beautiful live music. that‚Äôs the l.i.g.h.t. stories: described as ‚Äúthe vagina monologues meets ted talks, meets the moth‚Äú. on june 21st, come celebrate national indigenous day with us, listening to stories of humanity. these storytellers share an insight into the incredible healing powers that women hold within their own bodies, their relationship to their sexuality, and what it means to be a woman in their own terms. 
music by: the blue sky singers

doors open at 6:15 pm. the purchase of your ticket now includes a free-guided tour of the kw art-gallery's current exhibits, which starts at 6:30 pm. the light stories will commence at 7pm sharp. make sure to invite a friend! 
for all the bios on the storytellers, check us out on instagram or twitter and also use #lightstories2018 to have your pictures and comments shared on our ticket leap event page! 
if you would like to see some stories from our past events, please check our youtube channel.
.
.
.

text:
introducing the ‚Äúthe vagina monologues meets ted talks, meets the moth‚Äú.
i will be sharing my story "herstory" this thursday dec 20 evening at the @feminine_harbor and the kw art gallery present the light stories. 
if you missed out or loved the woke women's night held at @juiciyoga , this is for you. 
i am deeply honoured to know @carolinapmiranda and to be in relationship with the vehicle of change she is bringing to this community and to this world. buy your ticket in the event page below & invite a friend! hope to see you there!  feminine harbor and the kitchener waterloo art gallery present: the l.i.g.h.t. stories.

4 women, of 4 different generations and 4 diverse cultural backgrounds, sharing real-life stories combined with beautiful live music. that‚Äôs the l.i.g.h.t. stories: described as ‚Äúthe vagina monologues meets ted talks, meets the moth‚Äú. on june 21st, come celebrate national indigenous day with us, listening to stories of humanity. these storytellers share an insight into the incredible healing powers that women hold within their own bodies, their relationship to their sexuality, and what it means to be a woman in their own terms. 
music by: the blue sky singers

doors open at 6:15 pm. the purchase of your ticket now includes a free-guided tour of the kw art-gallery's current exhibits, which starts at 6:30 pm. the light stories will commence at 7pm sharp. make sure to invite a friend! 
for all the bios on the storytellers, check us out on instagram or twitter and also use #lightstories2018 to have your pictures and comments shared on our ticket leap event page! 
if you would like to see some stories from our past events, please check our youtube channel.
.
.
.

text:
a woman who says she was just 16 when she became woody allen's mistress in the 1970s is speaking out. babi christina engelhardt, who says she was a teen model when she met the famed director in 1976, opened up to the hollywood reporter about her alleged eight-year affair with the "annie hall" filmmaker. 
engelhardt, who now goes by christina engelhardt, told thr that she met allen at the restaurant and celebrity hotspot elaine's and  gave him her phone number. she said soon, allen, who was 41 at the time, called her and invited her to his fifth avenue penthouse apartment. 
engelhardt said allen never asked her how old she was, but she told him she was still in high school. 
engelhardt told thr that she and allen became physically intimate at his apartment within weeks, months before she turned 17, which is the legal age of consent in new york. 
the former model, now 59, said she has been thinking about it recently in light of the #metoo movement and controversy surrounding allen, whose adopted daughter dylan farrow has accused him of sexual abuse. engelhardt made it clear that she is "not attacking woody" and said she simply wants to provide perspective. "this is not 'bring down this man,'" she said in the interview. "i'm talking about my love story. this made me who i am. i have no regrets." she said that she was responsible for staying in the relationship. allen declined to comment for the story. engelhardt, now a mother of two, said that she was disappointed when allen introduced her to his "girlfriend," mia farrow, since she thought she was allen's girlfriend. but engelhardt said that she later participated in threesomes with farrow and allen. 
farrow declined to comment. 
she said that she knows actress stacey nelkin, who dated allen when she was 17, also says she was allen's "manhattan" muse, though engelhardt said, "i was like, 'whatever.'" she said she met two of allen's other young girlfriends during threesomes. but she appears to look fondly on the film, saying it reminds her "why i thought he was so interesting ‚Äî his wit is magnetic." read more at thr or cbs #metoo

text:
sorry, not sorry if i sound a little like grinch. but there is such inflated hype and pressure to exhibit cheer, goodwill and joy at this time of year that it‚Äôs easy to feel left out of the chocolate coated zeitgeist of christmas yumminess blasting at you in every store, on the radio in your car and everywhere you look. and even if you are in the middle of ‚Äúyour tribe‚Äù you can feel like an outsider looking in. the problem is over-blown expectation. it‚Äôs important to remember that christmas, like santa, is a consumer fantasy, meaning it‚Äôs not real or sustainable. so enjoy what you can and give yourself permission to acknowledge and validate any loneliness that‚Äôs coming up for you right now. there is nothing wrong with you and the sad or happy fact is this too shall pass. be extra gentle with yourself to balance out the hype.

here is a small clip from the beginning of my warm up today. i always warm up before i do any training session - even if it‚Äôs a slow striking form session.
.
.
.
in the first phase of my warm-ups i like focusing on light simple movements to get my heart rate up and warm up the muscles. then i go into a dynamic full body stretch (which isn‚Äôt shown in this video).
.
.
.
i love adding a striking twist to anything i do because it makes working out fun for me. if you want to give your warm-ups a fun striking twist, practice traveling in your survival stance or moving forward and backwards on the balls of your feet to help get your heart rate up for warm-up.
.

text:
i spent the greater part of 2018 in an emotionally abusive relationship with a narcissist. instead of taking over his gaslighting duties and blaming myself, i want to share what happened to internalize that it wasn‚Äôt my fault - a terrible person did a terrible, cruel thing to me (and plenty of other women), and this says nothing about me. putting the story out there makes me feel shameless as i should be. 
most of the photos i have at the taj mahal are of the two of us. it was our first date following a month of constant communication over the phone. i initially didn‚Äôt trust him, but he won me over when he started sending me videos introducing me to his friends and family, with all of them greeting me by my name. even during that trip, he talked about possibly coming to visit me in china, but i didn‚Äôt think he actually would. before i returned to china from india, i came down with a bad stomach infection that would end up lasting for over a month. he called me multiple times a day to check on me and give me advice from doctors and family members he had spoken to about my condition. a few weeks after our trip to the taj mahal, in the middle of march, he told me that he wanted to come to china to take care of me, and that he was in love with me and wanted to be in an exclusive relationship. of course, i thought it was too fast, and i‚Äôm not sure how i would have handled the situation had i not been in such a vulnerable position. i was sicker than i‚Äôd ever been in my life and far away from my closest friends and family - the idea of a hot dude coming to china to take care of me was really appealing, and by this point, he had already won my trust. 
by the time he came to china, i had finally been correctly diagnosed and started proper medication, though it would take a while for my body to completely heal. we were together uninterrupted for the month - he came to get me for lunch everyday after my classes, i took him to my favorite tourist spots on weekends, he would hold my hand and entertain me when i had to get iv‚Äôs at the hospital (they administered my antibiotics intravenously).

text:
#popbingewrapup18
-
glow
2x07: nothing shattered
#comedy #drama

with a tighter script and better use of the ensemble cast, glow has improved by leaps in its sophomore season, and it's hard to single out just one remarkable episode. 'the mother of all matches' was a wildly fun and deeply thoughtful episode that touches upon race, class, and motherhood. 'the good twin' lets loose, serving meta wackiness that highlights some of the best comedic moments of 2018; a distant sister to atlanta's 'b.a.n.' that wasn't received as well, as its no-fucks-given attitude rang false to some audience. the show also has its timeliest episode yet with 'perverts are people, too', bringing¬†#metoo to the 80's with¬†a frustrating weinstein-inspired plot. as well-crafted as those episodes are though, 'nothing shattered' really hit the mark for me.

picking up directly after an 'accident' during the live show, the episode follows the group as they anxiously wait at the hospital for some semblance of good news. meanwhile, the conflict between ruth and debbie finally boils over‚Äìand it is incredibly cathartic. for 1¬Ω season alison brie has held back so much; her character settled on being debbie's punching bag as her guilt somehow justified the treatment. great for gilpin as that allowed her to showcase such a devoted performance, but rather frustrating for brie because we've seen her do so much more both comedically (been a fan of hers since her annie edison days on community) and dramatically (trudy campbell on mad men, obviously). this episode finally showcases brie's range and it's incredibly satisfying, even more so as she basically did all those while being physically limited. it's also really satisfying how the episode handles the conflict without overshadowing the charming ensemble. those little moments between the different characters might not have contributed to the conflict directly, but that kind of attention to detail is what makes the show so honest and appealing.

glow has always been highly binge-worthy from the beginning (30 min episodes!), but it was unexpectedly great this season. with where the show is heading, i'm definitely amped up for its return next year.

text: you wake up, don't want to move, much less get up. but you do. you grab your coffee, you get dressed...but the world is heavy on your shoulders. take a breath. realize, you -did- get up, you -did- get dressed..you are still moving forward.  you are still living. even if you're doing it with tears on your face, slower steps...you -are- doing it! "down time" happens. it's ok. it's normal. no one can be perpetually bright and smiling! but never stop that forward step. even if that step is just opening your eyes when you wake!! raise your head and tell the universe "i-will- continue and i-will- succeed" and take that step forward into your day. accept all of yourself, even that darker less happy side. be whole. be accepting of all you are.üåπ#selflove #selfcare #selfdiscovery #wellbeing #wellness #jusssayin #settingboundariesandfsu #thetruthturnsmeon #boundaries #nocontact #redflags #narcissist #narcissisticabuse #narcissism #metoo #abuse #crazymaking #traumabonding #emotionalabuse #toxicrelationships #survivor #gaslighting #toxicpeople¬† #mentalhealthawareness #domesticviolence #believewomen #ifmywoundswerevisible #dontlookback #narcissisticabusesurvivor

text:
no solo quiero un 2019 en el que cada ni√±a y mujer vuelva a su casa sana y salva. 
quiero que cada vida de cada mujer de este planeta sea segura, desde que nacen hasta que mueren.

que no tengan que sufrir culpa si a alg√∫n energ√∫meno se le pone dura por ver un poco de escote, un culo firme o por ense√±ar algo de pierna.

que no tengan que aguantar acoso por la calle. qu√© exagerada! (estar√° pensando alguno). no se√±or. que t√∫ me silbes, me dirijas alg√∫n "piropo" o me inspecciones sin quitarme esa asquerosa mirada lasciva de encima es acoso. te lo he pedido? me conoces? me est√°s haciendo sentir inc√≥moda! 
que no tengan que sentir miedo cuando regresan a su casa de noche, cogiendo las llaves a modo de pincho por si tuvieran que defenderse. si queridos, yo, mi hermana, mis amigas... todas, o casi todas, nos hemos sentido as√≠ de inseguras en nuestra vida.

hablemos claro. 
yo, eva, recuerdo haber ido al cine con una amiga y sentarse un hombre a mi lado. era verano, yo llevaba un vestido vaquero. de repente sent√≠ un escalofr√≠o y una mano toc√°ndome desde la rodilla al muslo. sal√≠ corriendo. tendr√≠a unos 11 o 12 a√±os.
en otra ocasi√≥n, volv√≠a a mi casa en bus urbano con el uniforme del colegio, el bus llen√≠simo de gente, un hombre aprovech√≥ el momento para restregarse su polla contra mi culo. no tendr√≠a m√°s de 15 a√±os.
y a lo largo de mi vida he tenido que aguantar mucha mierda.

ahora soy madre de un ni√±o. qu√© gran responsabilidad! 
y qu√© m√°s da haber tenido un ni√±o o una ni√±a? no mucha, los hubiera educado a los dos bajo los mismos valores.
quiz√° enfatizar√≠a algunas cosas en seg√∫n qu√© caso.
pero el problema ser√≠a el resto del mundo, la sociedad.
y ya sab√©is de qu√© hablo: culpabilizaci√≥n de la v√≠ctima, lenguaje sexista, desigualdad salarial, menor representaci√≥n femenina en el √°mbito pol√≠tico, utilizar la imagen de la mujer como reclamo publicitario... lloro. 
lloro de impotencia, de rabia...
no hay igualdad. 
hay violencia. 
hay asesinatos! no son muertes joder, nos est√°n matando!

text:
and when you stare, i just wonder whether you'll understand what's going inside or you'll just see for the sake of staring. 
and when you stare, i just wonder whether you'll know what's pinching in my heart or you'll just see my body outside.
and when you stare, i just wonder whether you'll feel that i might be feeling awkward or you'll keep staring for you're too poor to feel.
and when you stare, trust me, i just wonder what exactly you see with this much zeal.

text:
every year i promised myself i'd write something. not just for the sake of it, or to be therapeutic, but to slowwwwwww people survivors are 1 in 3 women and yes someone you know. 
my emotional & mental journey while hardly talked about, has been one i've given my all to. at times felt i'm going a trail i didn't plan on starting, walking endless roads, climbing an up hill battle, i'm thankful i did. 
many things can change in year.
a year ago i felt ridden with overwhelming anxiety and feelings my words failed to articulate. night terrors walking up in sweat. moments of hindsight not wanting to speak, but wanting to be alone. a disinterest i n things i loved followed by helpless anger i wasn't loving it any more. ‚Ä¢

instead i now find myself with new found emotional time. instead of anxiety i now experience.... silence. 
not silence of uncertainty, fear, reluctance. a clarity. where i once slept in nightmares, i now sleep in dreams. where i once found no interest in what i loved, i've found myself enamored in new found passions, forming new traditions. ‚Ä¢

fortitude.
"mental¬†and¬†emotional¬†strength¬†in¬†facing difficulty,¬†adversity,¬†danger,¬†or¬†temptationcourageously"
‚Ä¢

i found my fortitude. 
and along the way, new aspects of myself.
the night is always darkest just before the dawn. 
and with fortitide, i rise.

text:
üíîrp @dxepriya when i reached inside of this baby calf's hutch, what i saw broke me. she was covered in diarrhea, which for calves can be extremely deadly. her filthy hutch had no bedding, no water, and no food. the only thing she could call her own is the ear-tag that was forcibly pierced into her ear when she was just a few days old. but the most haunting part of this experience was how lonely she was.
her loneliness is a routine practice in the dairy industry which depends on separating mothers from their babies. when julianne, alicia and i found angel at raymar ranch, she too was separated from her mom. but not only that, angel was thrown away like trash in a graveyard, waiting to die.

when i tried to help angel, she was ripped away from my arms. why is it that the industry sees us helping animals, their response is to punish us? it's because the truth is so scary that they feel it's criminal to publicize it.

if animal rights activists are considered criminals for trying to save baby cows from a life of misery and loneliness, we need more, not less of us. #dairyfree #dairy #govegan #crueltyfree #meat #hamburger #burger #pizzahut #pizzapizza #ilovepizza #cheesecake #cheesecakefactory #cheesey #cheeseboard #creamy #cream #creamcheese #dairyisscary #stopseparatingfamilies #burgerking #tacobell #burrito #quesadilla #vegano #metoo #seperation #donttakeourplanetforgranted

bundled up and got tea tonight, all alone. it was very hard/strange for me, but i did it with help of my walker. my face is finally starting to heal from my fall last week. it's still bruised, but the cuts are healing.
.
.
.
. 
i am looking for people who make hats. i get very cold, and i need to keep my head warm. i can't afford much, but please contact me.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
tanggal 25 november menandai hari internasional untuk penghapusan kekerasan terhadap perempuan. pada 10 desember, dunia merayakan hari hak asasi manusia. kita bersama yang mendukung  perjuangan pemenuhan hak perempuan telah memanfaatkan kekuatan dari dua tanggal yang berdekatan untuk #bergerak #16dayofactivism, sebuah kampanye internasional untuk mengakhiri kekerasan yang dihadapi perempuan dan anak perempuan di seluruh dunia setiap hari.
.
kampanye ini menegaskan bahwa kriminalisasi dan stigmatisasi aborsi adalah bentuk kekerasan terhadap perempuan dan anak perempuan. ini adalah pelanggaran hak asasi manusia untuk perawatan kesehatan, dan ini secara serius membahayakan keselamatan dan kesejahteraan jutaan perempuan setiap tahunnya. .
#endabortionstigma
#hearmetoo
#metoo
#aborsi
#aborsiaman

gray, de 24 a√±os, qued√≥ primera superando a las finalistas de sud√°frica, tamaryn green, y de venezuela, sthefany guti√©rrez, en un evento televisado presentado por el c√≥mico estadounidense steve harvey y la modelo ashley graham. 
en la √∫ltima ronda, gray arranc√≥ los aplausos del p√∫blico cuando habl√≥ de su trabajo en los barrios m√°s pobres de manila y dijo que, si ganaba el t√≠tulo, intentar√≠a buscar lugares ‚Äúdonde pueda dar algo, proporcionar algo‚Äù. tambi√©n explic√≥ que trabajar√° para un mundo ‚Äúdonde la negatividad no pueda crecer y aumentar, y donde los ni√±os tengan una sonrisa en la cara‚Äù. gray, que estudia musicolog√≠a, super√≥ a m√°s de 90 competidoras de todo el mundo en la 67¬™ edici√≥n de este concurso, que se celebr√≥ en el recinto impact arena de la capital de tailandia.

este a√±o el evento fue bien recibido por abordar temas como la inclusi√≥n y por un jurado formado solo por mujeres, incluyendo empresarias y antiguas miss universo.

la edici√≥n tambi√©n estuvo marcada por la representante de espa√±a en el concurso, angela ponce, de 27 a√±os, la primera candidata transg√©nero de la historia, que dijo querer representar la ‚Äúdiversidad de los seres humanos‚Äù. ‚Äúsiempre digo que a mi no me convirti√≥ en una mujer tener vagina.soy una mujer desde antes de nacer, porque mi identidad est√° aqu√≠‚Äù, dice ponce a la afp, se√±al√°ndose la cabeza.

text:
for me, this couldn‚Äôt ring more true... 12 years ago, i truly was at rock bottom. i‚Äôd just walked out of a courthouse. i‚Äôd been severely attacked by a man i loved.

i felt broken and defeated and lost. i‚Äôd thrown my entire life away. i‚Äôd dropped out of college. i was penniless. i had no car. i had no family or friends to turn to. i had no one left in the world and nowhere to go. i still wasn‚Äôt even safe...
.
part of me was so angry... but i also felt so *free* for the first time ever. i can‚Äôt explain where the feeling came from but i felt it, hard. i had freedom and independence. i may not have had any one or anything left... but i had myself.

so instead... i chose to rebuild. i chose to let go, take responsibility, and start from scratch - healing, rebuilding, and constructing a brand new life, one day at a time. little did i know that i would discover who i really was all along‚Ä¶

so no matter what you‚Äôre going through‚Ä¶ find the silver linings. find strength. find lessons. find yourself. you can rise, even in the wake of tragedy and devastating odds. it‚Äôs these times that equip us with all the skills we need to grow and succeed.
.
.
.
#leadthechange #bebrave #heal

text:
i'm behind on this album by like a month, but i'm loving a brief inquiry into online relationships by the 1975. especially love it if we made it, and i love america and america loves me.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
love it if we made it is about issues worldwide, but primarily about american issues. such as #metoo #blm and a lot of political issues and issues people have nowadays. hell, even lil peep's death was referenced in the song.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
i love america and america loves me is about gun control and stuff and my personal interpretation is that kids are afraid of what might happen any day at school and the government isn't listening to what we have to say at all. like kids just want to do their own stuff before they mature, but the adults aren't handling what needs to be handled so we're forced to somewhat take the matters into out own hands. "kids don't want rifles, they want supreme".
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
also i'm not a professional artist or review music by any means lol. i just love the message they send out and believe there's more meaning than what i even said.

text:
disney did a number on us.  so did nicholas sparks, and jerry mcguire. 
every where else in the world partners don‚Äôt expect their beloved to be their best friend, confidant, business partner and lover rolled into one. (the divorce rates are lower too)
elsewhere in the world we also don‚Äôt expect our beloved to fill our every need, coming into the relationship incomplete and then expecting and hoping that every need will be filled by the beloved. 
the strength in our beloved is a space for us to be.  be safe, be free to grow.  already full, already loved we come to the relationship to grow through love.  one of my favorite lines in the musical les miserables is, ‚Äúto love another person is to see the face of god‚Äù

ignite the fire is a program designed from my mistakes, thousands of client hours and research.  it‚Äôs designed for you to fill your own cup and heal. 
because when our own cup is full we really can see, hear and love. ‚ù§Ô∏èüíóüíöüíïüòç

gone are the days where i hid my gifts and knowledge in the shadows for fear of being perceived as ‚Äúweird, quirky, crazy, out-there, etc‚Äù. we are all spiritual beings having a physical experience with supernatural abilities just some are more aware of this than others. we are not humans having a spiritual awakening, we are spiritual beings having a human awakening. we are learning what it is to be human and we‚Äôve been lied to, controlled and conditioned to not believe in our own power because we are easier to handle that way. our actual ‚Äúnormal‚Äù is rapid manifestation, spontaneous healing of ourselves and others, regeneration and the list goes on. 
but tell us we are aging and declining and place higher value on youth so we spend on beauty creams and surgeries to meet some unrealistic ideal. burden us with high taxes and cost of living so that the stress makes us deteriorate and we give up the will to live. by the time most have learned and mastered the secrets of the universe they believe they‚Äôre too old to make the most of it and usually croak not long after as they have lost that will. what if you knew you were meant to live hundreds of years as a healthy and abundant being with plenty of time to do and be all that you wish to instead of resigning yourself to the belief you don‚Äôt have enough time in your comparatively short life to get it all done...? see what they‚Äôve done to you? and you think ‚Äúwhy would i want to spend hundreds of years on the hamster wheel of life anyway just to slave to pay bills and more taxes?‚Äù - well that‚Äôs exactly what they want you to think, feel and believe so that you willingly give your power away! ‚≠êÔ∏è‚ú®üí´ ‚Ä¢

text:
tw: ipv, abuse 
lacy was sexually assaulted and abused by her high school partner. as is common in intimate partner sexual violence, her partner used emotional manipulation to control and isolate her. though lacy had not yet told her friends of the abuse, they noticed her partner‚Äôs controlling behavior and helped her leave the relationship. ‚Äúno one understood what i was going through and what it was like in that relationship. but when we were apart, i realized how great it felt to be away from him‚Äîi really wanted that freedom.‚Äù lacy first disclosed the abuse to a friend over text, who then shared her messages with the former abusive partner. because of this, lacy didn‚Äôt feel comfortable disclosing to anyone else for a while. when she eventually opened up to her family, she faced disappointment and blame. ‚Äúat first, i felt i should have known better, i didn‚Äôt understand how i could let this happen to myself. i felt humiliated, and i was told i could not tell anyone about the abuse.‚Äù lacy faced continued abuse and harassment from the perpetrator after ending the relationship. he followed her around campus and called her continuously. ‚Äúhe didn‚Äôt want to let it go, he called me so many times my phone actually broke. i felt paranoid all the time; i‚Äôm still paranoid of the phone ringing. i had really bad anxiety and couldn‚Äôt sleep at night. i would find myself crying uncontrollably in the middle of the night.‚Äú
because of the abuse, lacy also experienced ptsd, anxiety, flashbacks, panic attacks, and stress-induced weight loss. lacy is thankful to her friends, who made an effort to support and protect her during this time. they made sure she didn‚Äôt walk home alone where the abuser could find and harass her and provided her with emotional support.

when lacy started college, she attended orientation events about consent and sexual assault prevention. these events gave her a platform to speak about what she had experienced and to fully realize the abusive nature of the relationship. ‚Äúfor the first year or two, i knew my relationship wasn‚Äôt a good one or a healthy one, but i didn‚Äôt label it as abusive.‚Äù
#25daysofsweaters #metoo

text:
i wrote this in solidarity with the¬†#metoo movement. - tell your story.¬†then tell it again.
-
just listen. -

women should build a barge,
a sturdy barge to float down a wide river.
strong enough to withstand any current, wind,¬†
no matter how they may rage.¬†
let them rage.
those who launch it will be the first to place their stories there.

others will know of its coming,¬†
line both river banks 
as far as the eye can see,
await it together, and holding hands wade out to it¬†
as it reaches them, each adding 
her very own story.

this mountain of stories will grow, 
becoming monolithic,
so imposing no world could ignore them, 
dismiss them,¬†
for one moment longer,¬†
not this many,
the sheer numbers of them.

here, the place where each woman‚Äôs story is finally heard,¬†
believed, unchallenged.
where each is given the chance to unfold itself 
in full,¬†
uninterrupted, within the woman's own time.
our vessel will accommodate all. 
every story heretofore untold, buried, unspoken,¬†
will join together there knowing
as sappho knew, what cannot be said 
will be wept.

and we will add yet more, one by one,¬†
as the barge makes its way downriver,
until every woman finds her voice there. 
we will moor the barge together,¬†
add kindling and thick logs atop it¬†
and at sunset, as one, set it alight, this tower of struggle and triumph,¬†
and the fire will be like no other. 
it will fill the sky and become 
part of the sunset¬†
and there will be no telling our flames apart from the fire in the sky as the day ends¬†
and women band together to send their stories skyward¬†
to all the galaxies that may be or ever were,
singing with one voice,
i remember,¬†
and yet¬†
i go on.
-

text:
the #bestalbumsof2018 list continues with... 7. @firstaidkitband ‚Äì ruins

best song: to live a life

it‚Äôs been a while between albums for first aid kit,with their last album being the pitch perfect stay gold in 2014. before ruins landed, there was a barn burning track that landed out of nowhere ‚Äì you are the problem here. as an acerbic song that landed just as the #metoo movement was beginning, you are the problem here suggested that there was going to be a change of tone for first aid kit going forward.

but, with that anger out of their system, they returned with ruins. a quiet album that is contemplative, reflective, and, as is expected from a first aid kit album,embraces the bond that johanna and klara have as sisters. ruins crosses genres, with a touch of folk and an element of country being blended into the mix, coming together to show a cohesive theme of growing from the troubles of your past. the quietest song on the album, to live a life, is also the most heartbreaking, with a single guitar gradually building to an immersive harmony that washes away any feeling of grief or sorrow that you may be holding onto, allowing you to be ok with the difficult decisions you‚Äôve had to make as your life rolls forward.

#bestalbums #firstaidkit #ruins #tolivealife

text:
one life to learn, grow and experience, whatever your dreams and ambitions are, never stop trying to reach them. whatever you want to experience, whatever your bucket list says, work out how to do it and get it done. believe in yourself and fill your life with joy. life will never be perfect and your plan will never stick exactly to how you planned it, but we are resourceful, when there is a will there is a way.
..
i have had lots of adversity in my lifetime, i know very well that life doesn't work out how you plan it. i have learnt to manage and be resourceful in the sense that my dreams and ambitions are very much the same, if not they have grown and i will always be striving to reach it. my motivation has only increased even though chronic pain and illness have become an issue to impact the way i love my life. i completely refuse to let it defeat me. if i do then my rapist wins, my abusive ex wins, everyone who has hurt me wins, i say not today, not tomorrow, not ever üôåüèªüôåüèª i am the master of my life and they will not have that power over me üëåüèªüôåüèªüôåüèª
..

text:
a federal high court sitting in osogbo has sentenced a former lecturer of obafemi awolowo university (oau), professor richard akindele, to two years in prison.

justice maurine onyetenu sentenced professor akindele on monday in osun state, at the end of his trial for demanding sex in exchange for marks from one of his students, miss monica osagie.

the accused had pleaded not guilty to the four charges of sexual harassment preferred against him by the icpc

when the case came up today, akindele opted to change his earlier plea and admitted guilty of the offences as charged.

p. s
we are glad with this judgment! as we continue to break the silence on sexual abuse and press for speedy trials of sexual abuse offenders! 
#saynotosexualabuse
#abuseisabuse
#speakout
#breakingthesilence 
#16daysactivism 
#metoo
@mirabelcentreng @wrinitiative @warif_ng @sexualabusesurvivorsstories @euinnigeria @unwomen

what is really disturbing is so many under the name of tantra saying they are doing healing but then calling their clients ‚Äúlovers‚Äù or they call themselves a mistress to the people they supposed to be working with on healing‚Ä¶if you are teaching tantra in sessions you are not lovers or their mistress, there is another name for that.

if you can‚Äôt take your own desires out of a session then don‚Äôt be working in this field. it really is as plain and simple as that. keep your clothes on in healing sessions as the

the pm had delayed the vote from last week, admitting she was set to lose.

to keep down the vomit from rising up my throat
the pain between my legs wasn‚Äôt planned
i begged to get out of there
and now i‚Äôm left feeling lost and hollow
.

text:
@karenavirginia and i connected thanks to another magical yogini, @seanecorn, who had shared on instagram some very cruel reactions to karena going public with her #metoo experience‚Ä¶
.
that happened to involve a very powerful man‚Ä¶
.
‚Ä¶the president. potus.
.
pause. deep breath.
.
what does it take for a woman to speak her truth in the face of massive inner and outer pushback?
.
we talked about this and so much more in this magical interview.
.
karena virginia has graced the cover of #yogajournal. she‚Äôs author of essential kundalini yoga. she‚Äôs featured in acclaimed yoga videos and meditation apps. she‚Äôs on #oprahwinfrey belief team. she was featured in #thenewyorker. in her beautiful ‚Äî almost uncanny ‚Äî humility, karena is reluctant to speak about her accolades and accomplishments.
.
we talked about the loneliness of being a drop before the wave that so many women thought leaders are experiencing. karena has always felt like that drop. she began studying kundalini yoga long before it was a ‚Äúthing.‚Äù before you could see yoga mats parade around new york city (it‚Äôs hard to imagine there ever was such a time). when there were 3 students in a class.
.
i felt such deep joy talking to a fellow pioneer and soul sister. the first question i asked karena was,
‚Äúwhen you first heard me use the words, patriarchy stress disorder, what did you feel and what did you think?‚Äù
.
karena said, ‚Äúi thought, ‚Äòthank you, dear god, for bringing this to our awareness.‚Äô it‚Äôs the feeling of being understood‚Ä¶ after having to work so hard to be understood.‚Äù
.
we talked about how this is such a common feeling for a woman ‚Äî having to work so hard to be understood.
.
how patriarchy stress disorder manifests in it feeling unsafe for us to show up in our full authentic expression.
.
how it impacts our connection with our inner guidance, with each other, and our ability to carry out our mission ‚Äî our big work in the world.
.
and so much more.
.
please listen to her success radio on your favorite podcast app. and if you find our conversations valuable, please subscribe and share with your friends.
.
have you ever experienced emotional or physical repercussions of speaking your truth or holding back?

text: happy hurts sometimes. there was a point in my life where i was so depressed that it took all my strength to simply get out of bed. i lived looking forward to the next time i could sleep,  and putting on a smile for the world was the most exhausting thing i could think of doing. being homeschooled and a full time gymnast made it easier to not have to be social. people on my gymnastics team just thought i was super quiet, and my family thought i was tired from training. i slept at every point i could. in college i got to the point where the thought of actually being normal and happy made me more sad. i fell in love with the darkness and couldn‚Äôt imagine my life without it. i just want to say if you feel alone in this fight‚Ä¶.you‚Äôre not. if you feel like its taking all your strength to put on a smile. you‚Äôre not alone. there‚Äôs nothing wrong if happy hurts right now. i am thinking of all of you (especially during this christmas season) who feel like you have to put a fake face of happiness for everyone around you. it‚Äôs exhausting. just know that its okay to not be okay. not everyone is as happy as they ‚Äúpost‚Äù they are, and you are not as alone as you think. message me if you need someone to talk to! ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
albums of 2018: 5‚É£
janelle monae - 'dirty computer'
.
release date: april 27th
country: united states
one word summary: defiant
listen to: django jane
.
2018 was the year that janelle monae officially stepped into the role that many gays had already appointed her: as the queen of queer. released in the face of rising anti-lgbtq sentiment in the u.s., and in solidarity with the growing #metoo movement across the globe, monae's dirty computer was far more direct and open than she'd ever dared to be on her previous two albums. it was a defiant musical statement; one that refused to simply roll over and take all the sexist, homophobic, racist and other divisive policies that were spewing forth daily from trump and his 'oppressed white upstanding christian american' goon army. and she did it all armed with little more than a funky prince synth riff, some trousers that looked like a massive fanny, and the rallying cry that, "if you fuck the world up now, we'll just fuck it all back down". love (and sex) always wins. ‚úäüåà
.

text: if we follow our enemies' propaganda, then i must say that is to be comparedwith "rejoicing towards heaven, depressed until death".the slightest success anywhere, and they literally turn somersaults in joy.they have already destroyed us, and then the page turns and again they are cast downand depressed. i did not want to attack in the center, not only because stalinknew i would. i provide one such example. if you read the russian telegramsevery day since june 22nd, they say the following each day: "fighting of unimportantcharacter". or maybe of important character. "we have shot down three times as manygerman planes. the amount of sunken tonnage is already greater than the entire navaltonnage, of all the german tonnage from before." they have so many of us missing thatthis amounts to more divisions than we can ever muster. but, above all, they are alwaysfighting in the same place. "here and there", they say modestly, "after fourteen days we haveevacuated the city." but, in general, since june 22nd they have been fighting in the sameplace. always successful, we are constantly being beaten back. and in this continued retreatwe have slowly come to the¬†caucasus. i should say that for our enemies, and not for your soldiers, that the speed at which our soldiershave now traversed territory is gigantic. and what has transcribed this past year is vast andhistorically unique. now, i do not always do things just as others want them done. i considerwhat the others probably believe and then do the opposite on principle. so, if i did not want toattack in the center, not only because mr. stalin probably believed i would, but because i didn'tcare about it at all. but i wanted to come to the volga, to a specific place and a specific city.it happened to have stalin's name, but that's not why i went there. it could have had another name.but, now this is a very important point. because from here comes 30 millions tons of traffic, includingabout nine millions tons of oil shipments. #meme #memes #fashion #art #blm #women #metoo #love #equalrights #proudtobe #pride

.
children who witness domestic violence are often expected to keep it a secret, leading them to blame themselves for the abuse, and experience sleep disturbances, feelings of fear and guilt, and depression.
.
if you are a child of domestic violence, remember that you overcame obstacles, you are accomplished, and no obstacle can compare. you are strong, you are resilient, and you are invincible.¬†üí™
.
